"The guy had just about everything, and he gives it all up?" Today's BTAS shot is from the episode titled "Moon of the Wolf" it is the 43rd produced and 36th to air. A lot of people would say...Batman vs a Werewolf? Is this a joke? This episode is actually based on a comic, Batman issue #255 which was written by Len Wein and penciled by Neal Adams! It Really is another good, yet underrated story of a man who was an Olympic Athlete, Anthony Romulus, and he loves being in the limelight as well as living the celebrity life, but as all athletes do, he starts to age as time wears on. He decides to stay on top he'll need help, and he gets it from the evil Dr. Milo. Milo uses a steroid werewolf formula which allows him to use the werewolf side as a slave to do his bidding. Milo realizes only Batman can stop his plans so he has Romulus take on the bat saying he'll cure him if he does. It's definitely different from the usual, but also very cool to see a an episode based on an old Batman v monster comic. "You are strong..but not strong enough! Farewell Batman!" Today's BTAS shot is from season 2 episode 16 titled "Day of the Samurai". We are taken to Japan to the dojo of Yoru Sensei, a man Bruce trained under. Here we see a young female named Kairi Tanaka, as she practices a ninja appears, knocks her out and drags her away, but while leaving a ransom letter for the Sensei. Naturally Yoru calls Wayne asking for aid, so he and Alfred pack their bags to help Bruce's old Sensei. Once there Bruce learns that Kyodai l, his former nemesis at the dojo is behind all this. He doesn't want money, he desires Yoru to teach him or give him instructions on "Kiba no Hoko" an ancient but deadly martial art taught to a select few. Batman delivers the map but Kyodai kicks Kairi off a ledge forcing Batman to save her and allowing Kyodai to flee. Kyodai finds the ancient scroll with instructions on Kiba no Hoko, but most of it is gone due to age, however he is able to learn a few things. He kidnaps Alfred in order to get Batman's attention and use his new found techniques. They meet at an active volcano for the last act and their final dual...which I leave for you to discover. Today's BTAS episode is from the episode titled "I am the Night" it is the 49th produced and 34th to air. We start by seeing a weary, mentally broken Batman slumped in a chair honestly talking to Alfred about how he doesn't know if he's making any difference. He can win a few battles, put away a few criminals, but they just get out and repeat the cycle. Alfred is so concerned he has Robin try to talk to Batman, but he doesn't get through either. The only thing that eventually shakes him out of his funk is when Gordon becomes injured due to Batman being late to the scene of a crime. I always enjoyed this episode because, let's be honest, outside of being a normal human, we tend to not have too much in common with Batman. However, this episode shows even Batman gets tired, depressed, questions it all being worth it, and I know I personally can relate to times of feeling this way as I'm sure most can if we're truthful with ourselves. However, Batman is able to overcome these feelings of doubt and depression and returns to full form by the end of the episode. Have a great day.

"You cured more than my body. You cured my heart." The next BTAS shot is from the episode titled "Mudslide" and it is the 52nd produced and 63rd to air. Matt Hagen, Clayface, is back...but only because he's not able to compose his claylike body anymore. He's falling apart, losing himself more  each day. He enlist the aid of a doctor and medical consultant who used to work on movies with him, Stella Bates. She is in love with Hagen and has her own mental issues, not being able to discern fiction from real life. She watches movies of Hagen, which she uses as motivation to get him back to who he used to be. Hagen is happy to feed her delusion by quoting the lines from those movies to her in order to keep that motivation high. Both sick, but both feeding each other's illness. Clayface has to steal in order to get the chemicals he needs to stay one piece, and once Stella finds an actual cure he steals that. Batman's been on his trail and figured out Hagen and Stella's plan. They have a showdown in the rain on the edge of a cliff before Clayface takes a final bow, or so it seems, this is the last time we see Clayface in BTAS.  Today's BTAS shot is from the episode titled "Zatanna" it was the 54th episode produced and 50th to air. It starts with Bruce Wayne attending his old friend Zatanna's magic show, Alfred ask how long it's been since he's seen her, and we see a flashback. In the flashback we see Bruce learning the art of magic and escape from Zatanna's father Zatara, gathering the tools to be Batman. In the flashback we see him also say goodbye to Zatanna, the last time he saw her till now. We get back to the magic show where Zatanna is at her big trick, which is making 10 million dollars disappear then return. She makes it disappear but can't get it to return! She's been set up, and because she doesn't have an answer, she is thrown in jail. Batman bust her out of a police transport and together they figure out who framed her and go after them. This is a very underrated episode in my opinion and it's one of the ones I really enjoy watching repeatedly. Especially seeing the relationship between Zatanna and Batman, Zatanna hints a few times she knows who he is and you can tell Batman has a soft spot for his old friend, not denying his identity but not confirming. The ending proves, even though it's fun reuniting with friends, goodbyes are always tough. Today's BTAS shot is from the episode titled "The Mechanic" it was the 55th produced and 48th to air. The episode starts off with us seeing Batman and Robin going after 3 of Penguins thugs, they get away and the Batmobile sustains major damage. The dynamic duo takes the car to a secret garage run by Earl Cooper and his daughter. He says he can fix it and gives Batman and Robin some motorcycles in the mean time. We than get taken to Penguins lair where an informant is telling Oswald that he's put together a list of parts the Batmobile would need based on the damage described, and has found that each of these parts were recently delivered to an Earl Cooper and they go after him. Friday August the 18th 2023 I underwent my 4th back surgery, my 3rd spinal fusion. It was horrible from the time I was put in a room to recover in the hospital. The first time I was told I should get up and walk I had a clear fluid leak through all my heavy bandages to where it was pouring onto the hospital floor. I had the feeling my head was going to explode, I was sweating through my clothes, about to vomit, and once I was back on my bed I was convulsing. This throughout my 6 days recovering at the hospital and it was text book signs of a Cerebral Spinal Fluid leak, where the membrane that held my spinal fluid in place and surrounding my brain was gushing out my back at an incredible pace. Yet the nurses at this hospital thought I was greatly exaggerating and wanted me to start a 3 times a day physical therapy routine. They tried kicking me out of the hospital to meet their metrics and look good on reports when I could barely make it to the bathroom without feeling like I was going to collapse. I was discharged with a soaking wet bandage that you could wring out and see my spinal fluid coming out like water. It refused to stop and the pain was greater than anything I have ever felt.  I tried going to the office of the surgeon that performed the surgery and could only get more bandages. I went to my nearest Emergency Room, told them I think I have a spinal fluid leak, they shot me with 2 more staples. The next day I had to go to an ER in Los Angeles, they finally took me seriously and actually took a CT scan and kept me overnight. I finally was able to be seen for a surgery that would help stop the leak. I had a half centimeter tear in the membrane of my spine fluid. I'm now home and resting, but still can't believe what I had to endure, how hard my family and I had to fight just to be seen, let alone get fixed before it was too late for me. I want to thank those of you who were aware of what was going on and kept checking on me and praying for me. Cherish every day you are healthy because it can all be gone in the blink of an eye, and could be taken by the very people you put your faith in to help you.

September 5th 1992 Batman the Animated Series made its debut and there's been nothing like it since. It gave us the definitive versions of every Batman character, to where if you're reading a comic you're most likely hearing Kevin Conroy as Batman, Mark Hamill as Joker, Arleen Sorkin as Harley, Richard Moll as Two Face, and I can go on. It not only gave us the best versions of Batman's rogues, but elevated others to new heights, such as Mr. Freeze, Clayface, the Ventriloquist and Mad Hatter. It produced new now classic Batman characters, the biggest being Harley Quinn,  Andrea Beaumont "Phantasm", Kyodai Ken, Nora Fries, Baby Doll, Renee Montoya, Roxy Rocket, Tygrus, the Condiment King and more. It is a show that didn't talk down to anyone, it didn't insult your intelligence. It is a show with depth and some powerful episodes, some more relevant now than they ever were. It led to more great spinoffs such as Superman the Animated Series, Justice League, Justice League Unlimited, Static Shock, and Batman Beyond. This Batman is focused, takes his job seriously, has a love for people, tries to save the villain and provide a way out of a poor lifestyle choice. We see him make mistakes, we see him grow, and we see it all executed perfectly. It was a show of its time yet way beyond its time. It is a masterpiece. #batmantheanimatedseries #batmantas #btas #brucetimm #pauldini #kevinconroy #markhamill #arleensorkin #thenewbatmanadventures #tnba

"...go back to where it all started, with toys. C'mon, be a kid again." 
Today's BTAS episode is titled "Riddler's Reform" it is the 79th to be produced and 73rd to air. Riddler has been declared reformed and thus freed from Arkham, so he goes into the toy business with Wacko Toys! Batman and Robin confront him to see what his angle is but he assures them he's gone straight. Crimes and theft start mysteriously happening but they have no tie to the Riddler, even though Batman can tell he's behind them. I think this is about as prime a Riddler story as one can get and it's my personal favorite in any medium due to how perfectly he's portrayed. In a lot of versions of the Riddler he just straight up proposes a riddle or sends Batman one and he has to figure it out and boom game over. However, in this episode he's saying he's not involved with the crimes on the surface, but when Batman really thinks about what he is saying, it's actually a clue to the next crime. Riddler does this throughout, leaving thinly veiled riddles while on toy commercials or responding to the dynamic duo and it's awesome how the riddles just come from him at all times and effortlessly, where if Batman leaves his guard down mentally, he'll fail. Like I said, Riddler in prime fashion. "Good old Bruce. He's never given up on me. Always been my best friend. I remember when we used to close the town at the Half Moon Club. The most fun we ever had..... Heard they were tearing the old place down. I guess nothing good last forever." Today's episode was the 80th produced and 72nd to air titled "Second Chance". Where do I begin? This episode explores how Harvey Dent is held hostage by Big Bad Harv in the one mind and body that makes Two-Face. At least that's my interpretation. Harvey was suppressing Big Bad Harv his whole life, the stress of his campaign brought that ugly side out more and he became scared, which physically manifested his dual persona. In this episode he's desperate to just be Harvey and the doctors feel he's mentally able to, but they want to do reconstructive surgery in order to help him feel whole and hopefully suppress the bad Harv. Just when he's about to be put under he's kidnapped. Batman goes looking for his former best friend, but he already knows the sad truth of the situation, Harvey did this to himself. He confronts Two Face, one on one, pleading with him to let him help. Two Face believes he's too far gone to be redeemed, the Harvey he used to be, is just a memory. Batman eventually hands him over to the cops, and Bruce is there to meet Harvey before he's taken away, Two Face sees him and the old Harvey peeks through one more time commenting how Bruce has "Always been there." It's sad knowing these two friends back story and seeing how far one fell, desiring to go back to normal, but also knowing down deep it can't be. I also love how Bruce is there, he may not be able to do anything at this point for Two Face, but he loves his friend, no matter what. #dccollectibles #dccomics #dcuniverse #dcmultiverse #dcicons #dcrebirth #dcanimation #dcrebirth #dcau #dcessentials #dceu #dcdirect #batmantheanimatedseries #secondchance #harveydent #brucewayne #brucetimm #pauldini #bigbadtoystore #mcfarlanemultiverse #soapstudioshk #mattel #kevinconroy

Bruce Wayne: You work with me, Tim, you follow the rules. Rule Number One: You give me everything you've got. Rule Number Two: Then you give me more. And Rule Number Three: I make the rules.

Today's BTAS shot is from season 4 episode 2 titled "Sins of the Father". It starts with a young man, Tim Drake, running from a cop after stealing his donuts. We see him get away by using an old batarang left by Batman at one point. Upon entering his apartment he's apprehended by two thugs asking for his father and then Two-Face enters to ask the kid as well. Eventually Batman appears and in the midst of trying to get Tim away Batman gets injured and has to take the batboat back to the cave and Tim's still with him! Alfred is shocked upon seeing this boy in the cave but tends to Batman's wounds. While that goes on Tim heads upstairs and figures out Bruce Wayne is Batman. He later ask about the Robin suit on display but Alfred tells him essentially that's a long story, and shortly after that he hears Batman tell Batgirl they found Tim's dad's body, killed most likely by Two face. Two Face eventually broadcast his plan to hold the city hostage with a massive bomb, demanding 2 million by 2am. Batman and Batgirl head for the Janus movie theatre after Tim tells them that it was Harvey's old hangout when his dad worked for him, but they tell him to stay back in the cave. He wants to help, and wants to get revenge on The man who killed his father as well. So he grabs the Robin suit and follows after Batman and Batgirl. Tim shows up and gets to confront Two Face, and the rest I leave for you! Today's BTAS episode is titled "Old Wounds" and it is the 17th produced, 18th to air. This is the episode that was probably tough for a lot to see, how the original Batman and Robin split ways. We see a Robin getting tired of Bruce's crazy expectations and desire to live his own life, a Batgirl who realizes her secret identity isn't that secret, and an Alfred ready to say he's Batman in order to protect Bruce's identity. There's a powerful and very memorable scene between Batman, Robin, and Batgirl that this episode is most known for. Inigo Montoya : My father was slaughtered by a six-fingered man. He was a great swordmaker, my father. When the six-fingered man appeared and requested a special sword, my father took the job. He slaved a year before it was done.

Man in Black : How old were you?

Inigo Montoya : I was eleven years old. And when I was strong enough, I dedicated my life to the study of fencing. So the next time we meet, I will not fail. I will go up to the six-fingered man and say, "Hello. My name is Inigo Montoya. You killed my father. Prepare to die."

RIP Richard Moll 1943-2023. Kevin Conroy, Mark Hamill, and Arleen Sorkin get their praises sung all the time when it comes to Batman the Animated Series, but let me tell you what, Richard Moll was killing it just as much if not more so each time he was on the show. From the moment you heard Big Bad Harv utter "Harvey..." in the dream sequence in Two Face part 1, the sadness in his "Good bye, Grace.." after his gutteral scream upon seeing his new complexion in the same episode. Part 2 he's just as good going nuts looking for his coin, and in Almost Got 'Em, Trial, Second Chance, Shadow of the Bat part 1 & 2, Sins of the Father, and Judgment Day he is on top of his game giving legendary reads to lines we quote to this day. Others know him from Night Court or some of the B movies he was in, but to this day I have yet to hear or see a better interpretation of Harvey Dent/Two-Face. #riprichardmoll #richardmoll #twoface #harveydent #batmantheanimatedseries #batmantas #btas #thenewbatmanadventures #tnba #batmantheadventurescontinue #twofacepartone #twofaceparttwo #trial #secondchance #judgementday #nightcourt #prettypoison #dccomics #dccollectibles #dcanimated #dcanimation

"Francine and March tried to protect me, but it was too late! The beast knew what chemicals were needed to bring itself about. It was out of my control. And it only needs one more component to complete the process. It's in me, Batman." Today's BTAS episode starts at season 1 episode 1 titled "On Leather Wings" with the main villain being Kirk Langstrom/the Man-Bat. Bruce Timm stated that they decided to do the first episode around a villain that people would not have anything to compare it to, such as the Joker, where everyone would have just critiqued whether it was better then Jack Nicholson or Caesar Romerero's interpretations. They wanted to let their work, story telling, and art be the focal point. We even get to see a Batman that the GCPD is still at odds with, not knowing if he's friend or foe. The animation in this really set the tone for the whole series and separated itself from anything that had been done before or since. Although this was the first episode produced, and officially the "pilot" the first episode to air was "Cat and the Claw: part 1". The reasoning for this was so fans could see a character they just recently saw in Batman Returns in Catwoman. All in all any fan of this show has a special place in their heart for this episode. Hope you guys enjoy these daily post! "Where's that bat fella, and that Robin fella? Ooo they're going to spoil my Christmas!" next BTAS shot is from the episode titled "Christmas with the Joker". It's now a  Christmas staple that sees the Joker breakout of Arkham Asylum on Christmas Eve while singing the now famous "Jingle Bells Batman smells". Batman and Robin catch wind of his escape and go looking for him, but Robin tries convincing his partner there's no way anyone would commit a crime on Christmas Eve. Eventually Batman relents and they go home to watch "It's a Wonderful Life" but instead they see the Clown Prince of Crime doing his own Christmas Special! He's got Gordon, Bullock, and Summer Gleeson all bound and is threatening to kill them if the dynamic duo can't reach him on time. It's a superb episode that even plays some Nutcracker music to Batman hitting toy planes!  Hamill is, of course, on his game throughout voicing Mr. J with maniacal glee, openly mocking Gleeson for crying due to her mom being on a train the Joker is about to blow up. "What's the matter, Scarecrow? Can't handle your own medicine?" 
Today's BTAS episode titled "Nothing to Fear". It's the first time most of us get to see Johnathan Crane, the Scarecrow! One of the first episodes I ever saw so its forever engrained on my brain.The episode starts with us learning Gotham University has been under attack and in need of money, so Bruce is at a fundraiser to help. He runs into someone who knew his father and the man gives Bruce a verbal lashing, telling him his dad would be ashamed of his lifestyle and legacy of the Waynes. Soon after that Bruce sees Scarecrow's crew heading into a vault and pursues them. While taking on Scarecrow's thugs he gets hit with a dart loaded with fear toxin, and we see it's not long before Batman is helpless. On top of that he sees his father in a hallucination and his father straight up tells Bruce that he has failed him, which is quite heartbreaking. Batman goes after Scarecrow later while stealing from the rich at another fundraiser for the University. Scarecrow is able to get to a blimp and Batman follows by climbing a hose on the outside. While hanging from the blimp he starts seeing his father tell him he's a disgrace again,  but this time he answers in the now famous line, "I am vengeance, I am the night, I am Batman!" For today's BTAS shot we get an all time classic Poison Ivy episode "Pretty Poison". We see Harvey Dent telling Pamela Isley, his girlfriend, about his best friend Bruce Wayne. Bruce was taking out some thugs as the Bat but arrives to meet his friend's love interest. It's nice seeing images of Bruce laughing and looking like he's genuinely happy too. Before long Pamela excuses herself, not before kissing Harvey good bye. It's only minutes before Dent passes out in his desert and is rushed to the hospital for poisoning. Bruce is beside himself and vows to find whoever did it this to his one true friend outside of Alfred. It's not long until some detective work shows Pamela Isely is behind the whole thing, as Poison Ivy! She catches Batman with a vine, poisons him, and explains she did it because Harvey built a penitentiary in a spot where a rare rose grew, and she only saved a precious few. Batman tries escaping while starting a fire in the green house, he's seemingly beat, he sees Ivy loom over him in a drugged daze, will he escape? How? "Help stop it Stromwell, all your power and money has bought you is an empire of misery. It has to stop Stromwell, it has to stop now." Today's BTAS episode is from season 1, the 12th to be produced but 6th to air titled "Its Never Too Late" This episode shows us Arnold Stromwell, an aging crime boss at war with Rupert Thorne for Gothams underground. The war is amplified due to Stromwell's son missing. Stromwell, of course, believes this to be the work of Thorne as a taunt to him, so he takes a meeting with him. On the way to this meeting Stromwell passes a rail road train station and we see a flashback that shows him stealing as a youth with a friend, Michael. Michael seems very responsible and gets onto "Arnie" for his theft letting him know it will catch up to him, but Stromwell was too proud even back then. Young Stromwell plays on the tracks and his shoe gets caught as a trains coming and..then we go back to present-day. Stromwell has a talk with Thorne but he hasnt seen his kid, Thorne flees leaving Stromwell in the restaurant with a bomb, but he's saved by Batman. Batman has sympathy for him, and takes him to his son who is at a drug rehab center. This gets Arnold furious saying he'll kill whoever got him hooked. His ex-wife replies, "Look in the mirror" The flashback memory of his train encounter, almost being blown up, seeing his son in a rehab hospital with his ex wife pointing out his drugs and lifestyle were responsible send Stromwell out of the room devastated. Batman then gives the quote above to Arnold, basically letting him know it's not too late to fix things. Stromwell however doesnt listen and back stabs Batman while looking for records to give to the GCPD. Rupert Thorne shows up and Batman has to subdue him and his men which he does. Stromwell we see has ran and he's st the train station and we see the rest of the flashback. He went from one track to the next, narrowly escaping once, but the train comes around a bend and is heading right for him when his friend Michael pushes him out of the way sacrificing himself for his friend. Definitely another powerful episode and quite possibly the most adult of them all.

This is how I shall always remember you: surrounded by winter, forever young, forever beautiful. Rest well, my love. The monster who took you from me will soon learn that revenge is a dish... best served COLD.

The next BTAS episode is the 14th produced, 3rd to air, and it needs no introduction, "Heart of Ice". Every so often we as fans of comics and their tie ins get treated to a story that feels bigger then the rest. As Batman fans we've been treated to a lot, Death in the Family, Killing Joke, Knightfall, Dark Knight Returns, Under the Red Hood, Flashpoint, Endgame, etc, you catch my drift... stories that are game changers. Well, when you mention Batman the Animated Series, outside of Kevin Conroy and Mark Hamill's perfect portrayals of their characters, I'm pretty sure most fans have this episode come to mind. It's a beautifully haunting tragedy of a man who unfairly lost his wife and just wanted to save her. I think when this episode aired every one stopped and took notice that this show was not some silly thing for kids, but was meant to be something more and stand the test of time, which it has. It's not my personal favorite, but I can't deny it's almost a perfect episode and reinvigorated a character most thought idiotic. "Perfect my love, let's go home." Today's BTAS episode is from season 1, the 1st episode to air and 15th produced and is part one of two, titled "The Cat and the Claw". We start off with  Catwoman breaking into someone's house and using her cat to get some jewels. However, Batman shows up and they have their first chase across the roofs of Gotham. Catwoman has the full attention of the terrorist group now and almost escapes but starts to fall from a building when Batman gets her. While swinging to safety Catwoman gives him a kiss as a thank you. Then she slips away and we are left to wait for the next episode for the conclusion. Gordon: Something for the lab boys to play with, any idea what it is?

 Batman: Yes, the stuff that dreams are made of.

 This might be your answer too, if you had just been ripped away from a perfect world. Today's BTAS shot is from the episode titled "Perchance to Dream" it is the 30th produced and 26th to air. This episode has always been really close to being my number 1 and it may even be 1b behind the "Feat of Clay" episodes. The entire episode has you on the edge of your seat wondering what's going on, and you're kind of confused the entire time, sort of like a real dream. Bruce Wayne wakes up one morning to find everything in his life is perfect. He's not Batman, he's engaged to Selina Kyle, and his parents are alive and in great health, perfection! But just how we the audience know something's not quite right, Bruce feels it too. He feels Batman has something to do with it so he goes to a patrol spot at a bell tower he usually goes to nightly. There Bruce confronts the imposter and eventually removes the mask revealing Mad Hatter! The episode only gets better from there with the writing  being prime BTAS, creating stories that just fire on all cylinders. Batman fans were spoiled with this one, all time classic. "I've waited a loooong time." The next BTAS episode is titled "Robin's Reckoning Part 2" it's the 32nd/33rd to be produced and 51st/53rd to air. In this episode we see the origin of Robin/ Dick Grayson. We see his parents death at the hands of Tony Zucco at Haley's Circus. Bruce happened to be in attendance and decided he was going to adopt young Grayson. We see Bruce eventually reveal he's Batman and start the relationship of the original dynamic duo. Only one problem, Bruce has hidden who killed Robins parents from Dick to protect him from acting out violently in a rage towards the man and do something he would regret. Robin finds this out though while being left behind and goes after Zucco himself. He eventually finds him and the scene is filled with emotion. You see Robin in full on wreck mode as he drags Zuccos body like a rag doll while on his motorcycle. He then whoops him up a bit then dangles him near the edge of a pier. As he speaks you hear pure anger/rage as he looks into the fearful eyes of his parents murderer. One more push and he could end Zucco, but Batman gets to him and talks him out of his emotional rage. The episode ends with Zucco in jail and Robin doing the right thing. It's a well crafted, emotional episode that is beautifully done because it wasn't rushed and they expanded it to the two parts, highly recommended this one. #dccollectibles #dccomics #dcuniverse #dcmultiverse #dcanimation #dcanimateduniverse #dcau #dc #batmantheanimatedseries #batmantas #btas #thenewbatmanadventures #tnba #robinsreckoning #robinsreckoningpart2 #tonyzucco #thedynamicduo #dynamicduo #batmanandrobin #dickgrayson #theflyinggraysons #robin #theboywonder #boywonder #brucetimm #pauldini #bigbadtoystore

"You are strong..but not strong enough! Farewell Batman!" Today's BTAS shot is from season 2 episode 16 titled "Day of the Samurai". We are taken to Japan to the dojo of Yoru Sensei, a man Bruce trained under. Here we see a young female named Kairi Tanaka, as she practices a ninja appears, knocks her out and drags her away, but while leaving a ransom letter for the Sensei. Naturally Yoru calls Wayne asking for aid, so he and Alfred pack their bags to help Bruce's old Sensei. Once there Bruce learns that Kyodai l, his former nemesis at the dojo is behind all this. He doesn't want money, he desires Yoru to teach him or give him instructions on "Kiba no Hoko" an ancient but deadly martial art taught to a select few. Batman delivers the map but Kyodai kicks Kairi off a ledge forcing Batman to save her and allowing Kyodai to flee. Kyodai finds the ancient scroll with instructions on Kiba no Hoko, but most of it is gone due to age, however he is able to learn a few things. He kidnaps Alfred in order to get Batman's attention and use his new found techniques. They meet at an active volcano for the last act and their final dual...which I leave for you to discover. Today's BTAS episode is from the episode titled "I am the Night" it is the 49th produced and 34th to air. We start by seeing a weary, mentally broken Batman slumped in a chair honestly talking to Alfred about how he doesn't know if he's making any difference. He can win a few battles, put away a few criminals, but they just get out and repeat the cycle. Alfred is so concerned he has Robin try to talk to Batman, but he doesn't get through either. The only thing that eventually shakes him out of his funk is when Gordon becomes injured due to Batman being late to the scene of a crime. I always enjoyed this episode because, let's be honest, outside of being a normal human, we tend to not have too much in common with Batman. However, this episode shows even Batman gets tired, depressed, questions it all being worth it, and I know I personally can relate to times of feeling this way as I'm sure most can if we're truthful with ourselves. However, Batman is able to overcome these feelings of doubt and depression and returns to full form by the end of the episode. Have a great day.

 Today's BTAS shot is from the episode titled "Zatanna" it was the 54th episode produced and 50th to air. It starts with Bruce Wayne attending his old friend Zatanna's magic show, Alfred ask how long it's been since he's seen her, and we see a flashback. In the flashback we see Bruce learning the art of magic and escape from Zatanna's father Zatara, gathering the tools to be Batman. In the flashback we see him also say goodbye to Zatanna, the last time he saw her till now. We get back to the magic show where Zatanna is at her big trick, which is making 10 million dollars disappear then return. She makes it disappear but can't get it to return! She's been set up, and because she doesn't have an answer, she is thrown in jail. Batman bust her out of a police transport and together they figure out who framed her and go after them. This is a very underrated episode in my opinion and it's one of the ones I really enjoy watching repeatedly. Especially seeing the relationship between Zatanna and Batman, Zatanna hints a few times she knows who he is and you can tell Batman has a soft spot for his old friend, not denying his identity but not confirming. The ending proves, even though it's fun reuniting with friends, goodbyes are always tough.
